  "active_lock_reason": null,
  "body": "Problem: Web3 0.x returned numbers as BigNumber (or BN) objects. Web3 1.0 returns them as strings, IIRC they made this change because they thought the lib should be agnostic about how large numbers are managed and strings are common to all the solutions. \r\n\r\nUnfortunately this is moderately catastrophic for large existing test suites. Was not enthusiastic about coercing the new outputs back into the old format because:\r\n\r\n+ it's complicated, we'd have to read the ABI and handle all the different data structures that might have numbers nested in them. \r\n+ truffle-contracts behavior should be isomorphic to web3's - it's injected into the test context and its methods can be called independently.\r\n+ web3 is likely right about handling numbers in this simpler way? \r\n\r\n**Damage Survey**\r\n\r\nZeppelin uses chai-bignumber / BigNumber and has ~550 occurrences in their suite.\r\n```\r\nbalance.should.be.bignumber.equal(amount);\r\n```\r\n\r\nColony's `colonyNetwork` has ~400 occurrences of the `.toNumber()` method (which is common to BN and BigNumber). \r\n```\r\ntask1[5].toNumber()\r\n```\r\nThe colony case might have a simple resolution - we should be able modify the String prototype for the test context to be something like:\r\n``` \r\n> String.protoype.toNumber = function() { return parseInt(this) };\r\n> '5'.toNumber();\r\n5\r\n>\r\n```\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n",
